import java.util.ArrayList;

public ArrayList<Integer> divisibilityArray(String word, int m) {
    ArrayList<Integer> div = new ArrayList<>(word.length());
    int value = 0;
    for(int i = 0; i < word.length(); ++i) {
        value = (value * 10 + (word.charAt(i) - '0')) % m;
        div.add((value == 0) ? 1 : 0);
    }
    return div;
}
```

    We initialize an empty divisibility array and a variable value to store the current numeric value. We iterate through the characters in the input string word. For each character, we multiply the value variable by 10 and add the numeric value of the character by subtracting the ASCII value of '0' from the ASCII value of the character, then taking the remainder with m. If the value is equal to 0, we push 1 in our array, and otherwise, we push 0. Finally, we return the divisibility array.
